Name: AVRIL TAN XIN YI
Content:
Today Iâ€™m officially 30. âœ¨

When I was in my teenage years, I used to think that by 30, Iâ€™d have life all figured out. I imagined having everything â€œperfectlyâ€in place â€” be it my career, relationships, direction, confidence, I looked at adults around me thinking that once I grow up, I would have it all together. 

But as I age, I realise life isnâ€™t about having it all figured out. 

Itâ€™s about embracing the unknown, growing through the seasons, and learning to be okay with not having all the answers.

For a long time, Iâ€™ve felt like I was behind â€” like I was lagging in the game of life while everyone else seemed to be moving faster, achieving more, checking off all the boxes. 

But over time, Iâ€™ve come to understand that weâ€™re all running our own race. Thereâ€™s no set timeline, no â€œrightâ€ pace. Just progress, presence, and purpose.

Looking back, Iâ€™m so grateful for the journey â€” the highs, the lows, the moments that broke me, and the ones that built me. I wouldnâ€™t be who I am today without every twist and turn along the way.

And most importantly, Iâ€™m deeply thankful for the people whoâ€™ve been part of this ride â€” the ones who stayed, the ones who left, the ones who taught me lessons and the ones who continue to love and support me as I grow.

Hereâ€™s to entering this new decade with an open heart, steady faith, and a lot more grace. Iâ€™m excited for whatâ€™s ahead.

I may not have it all figured out, but Iâ€™m learning to trust the process â€” and thatâ€™s enough.

We were born free,
but from the moment we entered this world, labels quietly found their way onto us.

â€œObedient,â€ â€œclever,â€ â€œaverage,â€ â€œa failureâ€â€¦
Society uses these labels to define worth,
and in our need for approval, we learned to conform â€”
seeking validation under the weight of expectations.

But deep inside, weâ€™ve always been resisting.
The desire to truly be ourselves never disappeared â€” just buried under layers of life.

One day, we begin to see clearly:
these labels were never who we really were.
We can choose to peel them off,
and become who we were meant to be.

True freedom isnâ€™t reckless.
Itâ€™s choosing with awareness, growing with discipline,
and living by values we define for ourselves.

That is strength â€” and a higher kind of freedom.

16 Years in the Business | 17 April 2025

I was just 21 when I RNFâ€™d - wide-eyed, full of hope, with a simple dream: To make a real difference in peopleâ€™s lives, especially the ones I loved.

I still remember what my leaderâ€™s mentor told me back then:
â€œIf you do this right, with sincerity and service, youâ€™ll never run out of people to help.â€

Back then, I had no idea how deeply this journey would shape me. I just knew I wanted to be someone others could count on.

Fast forward 16 yearsâ€¦
440 clients. Countless moments of courage, care, and conversation.

Still here.
Still growing.
Still giving from the heart.

Grateful for every person whoâ€™s been part of this story -
Clients who became friends, friends who became clients, mentors who saw more in me than I saw in myself and my tribe whoâ€™ve stood by me through every season.

Hereâ€™s to the journey ahead.
The best is yet to come.

Name: CHENG LI CHIANG STEVE
Content:
Part 1 
âœ¨ Take Responsibility for Our Own Success âœ¨

Just listened to the legendary Tony Gordon â€” expelled from school at 16.
Written off by teachers. Doubted by friends.
Today, at 79, he stands as one of the greatest icons in the insurance world.
A true GOAT.

He ended his sharing with this powerful truth:

â€œTake responsibility for our own success.
If things arenâ€™t going our wayâ€¦
Is it the companyâ€™s fault? Our managerâ€™s fault? Other peopleâ€™s fault?
NOâ€¦ HELL NO!â€

That hit deep.

My biggest takeaway?
Weâ€™re not stuck.
Weâ€™re not stone.
We can move.
We can change.
We can find solutions.

â€œWe are not a stone. We can move.â€

So letâ€™s:
â¡ï¸ Stop blaming
â¡ï¸ Stop pointing fingers
â¡ï¸ Keep moving
â¡ï¸ Keep failing forward
â¡ï¸ Keep growing
â¡ï¸ Keep becoming better

Every get-up brings us higher.
Letâ€™s keep climbing â€” together.

A very good reminder to self. - Part 1

Name: CHENG LI CHIANG STEVE
Content:
Part 2
Disclaimer: not trying to be disrespectful to anyone. Pardon the AI effect. 

â€œSir, I just want to shake your hand.â€
(He gave me a weird stareâ€¦ and a gentle smack on the arm.)

After listening to the legendary Tony Gordonâ€”the GOAT of the insurance industryâ€”share his story, I was deeply inspired.

At 79, he flew from the US to Malaysia just to spend an hour with us. He couldâ€™ve stayed in the comfort of home, or travelled with friends. But he chose to be hereâ€”to give, to serve, to lift others. That alone taught me something: greatness doesnâ€™t retire.

After his session, everyone rushed to take photos. I couldnâ€™t get close, so I cheekily â€œphoto bombedâ€ and AI-ed myself closer in Photo 1.

But eventually, as the room cleared, we got a proper photo with him.

Then came my moment.
I walked up, extended my hand, and said:
â€œSir, I just want to shake your hand.â€

He looked at me with a confused stareâ€¦ then gave me a light smack on the arm.

I wasnâ€™t trying to be cheeky or disrespectful.
I just wanted to feel the warmth of his hand.
To remind myselfâ€”heâ€™s human. Just like us.
Same warmth. Same heart. Same opportunity to do something great with our lives.

Iâ€™m grateful for this journey.
Grateful for the team and family weâ€™ve built at PFG.
And grateful even for the tough daysâ€”because theyâ€™re shaping us for something greater.

Letâ€™s keep going.
Because if he can, we can.
If he did, so can we.

A good reminder to self. - Part 2

Name: CHOO WEIJIE, BENJAMIN
Content:
I walked into my 32nd year thinking it was going to be just another quiet birthdayâ€¦
But what unfolded was a humbling, heartwarming reminder of what truly matters in life. Hereâ€™s what I learnt:

Name: GWYNETH LIM YING XUAN
Content:
HE IS RISEN 

John 3:16 For God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son, that whoever believes in him shall not perish but have eternal life. 

Watched Passion of the Christ yesterday and reflected on it: 

I saw an image of myself in Judas - There were times where I turn myself away from him just because things didnâ€™t go my way. But despite all these, he waited for me patiently to go back into his arms. 

When Jesus was carrying the cross and fall, Mary ran towards him - It showed me how Jesus was there for me when I fall, being with me throughout. 

When the Romans was hitting him until he was covered in blood, with his flesh and ribs visible. He could have used his power to not go through all these, but he knows he has to fufil his purpose that by his stripes, we are healed. 

Even when Jesus was on the cross, he still show grace and told god to forgive them, for they donâ€™t know what they donâ€™t know. I thought to myself: â€œWho am I to not forgive and show grace to others for god choose to forgive us even though we are sinners.â€

Name: JARED THAM JIA LE
Content:
3 ğ‘¨ğ’…ğ’—ğ’‚ğ’ğ’•ğ’‚ğ’ˆğ’†ğ’” ğ’ğ’‡ ğ‘©ğ’–ğ’šğ’Šğ’ğ’ˆ ğ‘°ğ’ğ’”ğ’–ğ’“ğ’‚ğ’ğ’„ğ’† ğ‘¬ğ’‚ğ’“ğ’ğ’š (ğ’•ğ’‰ğ’‚ğ’• ğ’ğ’ğ’”ğ’• ğ’‘ğ’†ğ’ğ’‘ğ’ğ’† ğ’…ğ’ğ’'ğ’• ğ’Œğ’ğ’ğ’˜ ğ’‚ğ’ƒğ’ğ’–ğ’•) 

So, you're a young adult, right? 

It's great to be young and carefree, but as you start to take on more responsibilities and make your way in the world, some areas that we usually overlook is our physical and financial health. 

While Iâ€™m not a health coach or fitness trainer that can provide you the expertiseâ€¦

I can help with the insurance portion ;P
 
It's not the most exciting topicâ€¦ but something you really can't afford to ignore. 

So, if you're ready to learn more about why insurance is important for young adults like you, dive into this post and explore the benefits of getting covered when you're young.

âœ…Cheaper Premiums When Younger
Did you know that you can lock in your premiums at cheaper prices? 

Life insurance premiums are based on several factors, including a person's health and age. Generally, the amount you pay to purchase a life insurance policy rises as you age. 

Rates can jump considerably if you wait until you are in your mid-thirties or forties due to the higher probability that the insurer will have to make a pay out on the policy you purchased. 

âœ…Guarantee your Insurability 
Many people think they can buy insurance with moneyâ€¦.

Sorry to burst your bubble but unfortunately that isn't the case. 

You buy insurance primarily with your health. 

Almost ALL insurance policies have exemptions for pre-existing conditions, which means if you have a medical 
issue now, and buy insurance later, you won't be covered for that condition. 

The inevitable fact is that our health deteriorates as we age. Buying insurance when you're young and healthy lessens the need for medical check ups or more underwriting. We hope to be healthy forever but what if you and I are both wrong? Will it be too late?

âœ…Financial security in your Prime years ensures that you can focus on recuperating, even if it takes several years, without having to worry about paying for basic needs or family responsibilities.

And after almost 5 years in the industry, I can safely say, you will never be able to put a put a price tag on peace of mind

Name: LIM POH NGO JENNIFER (LIN BAO'E)
Content:
Will you buy your medical plan? 
I did.

I am not that fortunate to have my mum or dad to buy for me, i dont think they even know what insurance can do.

Today, I have a new perspective on being an insurance agent (in case those who donâ€™t know what I am doing still) 

It is because I learned to buy this protection, called â€œinsurance,â€ for myself in my younger days. I know I have done some form of risk transfer, and I like to help some (not all, as I cannot save everyone) to have what I have. 

As I start to prep for this thing call â€œretirementâ€, I want to also start helping other to do the same.

#sharing
#jenniferlimpn
#æ—ç¾å²„
Jennifer Lim - Singapore

Name: LIM WEI MIN
Content:
Hereâ€™s a photo of me, receiving my first ever award during an agency townhall meeting back in 2017.

A little bit of my journey leading up to that moment.

After NS, I stepped into Insurance straight. I heard it's sales and I can earn a lot of money, so why not? ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™‚ï¸

But I had my struggles in the initial 8 months. I was only earning $1.8k in total. I almost gave up (I was in debt during that time as well).

Looking back, Iâ€™m glad I didn't give up. I feel that credit for my career breakthrough goes to both â€œperseveranceâ€ and â€œluckâ€. Breakthrough is something you have to be ready for, and when the element of luck comes, you break through. Breakthrough doesnâ€™t come â€œjust like thatâ€ because you learn and worked hard.Â 

Since then, warm cases started to come in and I earned my first $10k. Subsequently, sales were good and I even got married soon after ğŸ˜„

So if you're having a tough start or hesitating because you're afraid of the hurdles, remember this: perseverance and readiness can turn even the smallest opportunity into a breakthrough. Keep pushing forward and your moment will come just like mine did!

#careerjourney #nevergiveup #breakthrough #careersuccess #empowerment #personalgrowth #mentorship #financialadvisory #financialconsultant #financialservices

Name: MAGESWARAN S/O DEVADAS
Content:
Why Every Sales Professional Needs Systems

In the fast-paced world of sales, success does not come by chance. It comes by design. And one of the most powerful tools a salesperson can have is a system.

When we talk about systems in sales, we are referring to a structured approach. A repeatable, reliable process that guides how we find leads, nurture relationships, present solutions and close deals. It is about turning daily chaos into a well-oiled machine.

Why does this matter?

Because systems drive productivity. They save time, reduce stress and eliminate guesswork. They help us prioritize the right clients, follow up at the right time and track the right metrics. With systems in place, we do not just work harder. We work smarter.

Imagine knowing exactly what your next step is with every prospect. Imagine having automated follow-ups that go out like clockwork. Imagine being able to train new team members with ease because everything is already mapped out.

That is the power of systems
They bring consistency
They create scalability
And most importantly, they deliver results

Sales is not just an art. It is a science. And systems are what turn potential into performance.

If you are in sales and want to rise above the noise, build your systems

Name: NOR MUHAMMAD ALIF BIN ADNAN
Content:
Alhamdulillah. Yesterday we had the honour of hosting our loved ones for Raya.

It wasnâ€™t just an ordinary visit â€” it held deep meaning for us.
29 and 27 years ago, my wifeâ€™s parents left (passed away) her and her siblings at a young age.
Since then, it was abang who stepped up â€” carrying both roles â€” always there to guide, support, and protect them like his own.

Being able to welcome him and his family into our home this Raya brought a different kind of warmth.
Seeing the kids â€” the cucus â€” laughing, playing, and bonding so naturally made us feel as if Ayah and Ibu were with us too, smiling over the gathering.

Moments like these remind me â€” itâ€™s not about how grand the house is or how lavish the spread.
Itâ€™s about the barakah in the hearts that fill the space.

Alhamdulillah for blessings that words sometimes cannot even describe.

Name: WEE LI TING
Content:
[13 April 2025 | Bali, Indonesia]

This year, I made a spontaneous decision by booking a solo trip to Bali for my birthday. Behind the spontaneity was a quiet need for something more - more clarity, more courage, more connection with myself. The thought of being alone in an unfamiliar place can be intimidating. But thereâ€™s no one to distract me, from me. And in that silence, I started to listen. I listened moreâ€”to the world around me and to myself. I noticed the little things: the art that spoke to me, dogs chasing waves, the sound of the ocean crashing onto shore. I confronted thoughts and feelings I usually drowned out with busyness. I learnt to appreciate my own pace, my own rhythm. I celebrated myself for the first time and celebrated with strangers who I may never meet again. And in all of that, I found a deep fulfilling sense of freedom ğŸ«¶ğŸ»
